      "text": "DAILY MARKET UPDATE - January 16, 2024 \nEarly Morning Update\nThe Feb ’24 natural gas contract is trading down $0.37 at $2.95. \nThe Feb ‘24 crude oil contract is down $0.03 at $73.56.\nSummary\nVarying weather forecasts have made the specifics of this nation\u0002wide cold snap hard to predict, but most everywhere in the \ncountry has experienced some portion of Winter Storm Heather \nover the last few days. Nationwide gas prices for delivery over the \nholiday weekend surged by nearly $13/Dth on average on Friday, \nwith the most significant movements upward in the Midwest and \nMidcon regions. Power index pricing across the country has also \nbeen strong, with real-time on-peak pricing in Texas around $100 \nto $150/MWh yesterday, PJM day-ahead on-peak pricing around \n$150/MWh, and some points in MISO close to $170 in day-ahead \non-peak pricing. Natural gas production has dropped about 9% \nvs. this time last week, due to weather-related freeze-offs. \nWeather-induced production cuts are typically sh",
      "highlights": [
        ".56.\nSummary Varying weather forecasts have made the specifics of this nation\u0002wide cold snap hard to predict, but most everywhere in the country has experienced some portion of Winter Storm Heather over the last few days. Nationwide gas prices for delivery over the holiday weekend surged by nearly $13/Dth on average on Friday, with the most significant movements upward in the Midwest and Midcon regions. Power index pricing across the country has also been strong, with real-time on-peak pricing in Texas around $100 to $150/MWh yesterday, PJM day-ahead on-peak pricing around $150/MWh, and some points in MISO close to $170 in day-ahead on-peak pricing. Natural gas production has dropped about 9% vs. this time last week, due to weather-related freeze-offs. Weather-induced production cuts are typically short-lived and should alleviate within a few days once temperatures begin to climb again. The Midwest will continue to feel the brunt of this artic chill over the next day or two, with a slight reprieve, and then colder temps returning for another visit this weekend nearly everywhere east of the Rockies. A general, wide-spread warm-up is currently forecasted to start off next week, which would be a \nwelcomed change to current frigid conditions. Bearish Factors Bullish Factors \n• Robust natural gas production • Below-normal temperatures • Very healthy natural gas storage • Increasing res/com demand\n• Low global LNG prices • Future LNG export growth Next Day On-Peak Power (traded for 1/16/2024)\nISO-NE Mass Hub\n$180.00\nMISO Indiana Hub \n$233.85\nNYISO Zone G\n$188.49 PJM West Hub\n$145.51\nERCOT North\n$460.70\nCAISO SP15\n$151.26\nEIA Natural Gas Storage\nEIA Reported \nStorage (Bcf)\nThis Week\nLast \nWeek\nLast\nYear\n5-Year \nAvg.\nTotal 3,336 3,476 2,900 2,988\nDiff v. Current -140 436 348\n% Diff 15.0% 11.6% NYMEX NG Close Change\nFeb-24 3.313 0.216\nMar-24 2.617 0.077\n12-Month 3.079 0.071\nCal 25 3"
